The "Newline Pitfall" (Important)
If you use nextInt() followed by nextLine(), the nextLine() often seems to be "skipped."
This happens because nextInt() leaves the "Enter" character (newline) in the buffer.
The Fix: Add an extra sc.nextLine() to "consume" that leftover newline.

System.out.print("Enter age: ");
int age = sc.nextInt(); 

sc.nextLine(); // This consumes the leftover newline character

System.out.print("Enter your favorite quote: ");
String quote = sc.nextLine(); // Now this will wait for your input!




Method,                            Description,                                  Example
length(),                          Returns the number of characters.,            str.length();
charAt(int i),                     Returns the character at a specific index.,   str.charAt(0);
substring(int start, int end),     Extracts a portion of the string.,            str.substring(0, 5);
toLowerCase() / toUpperCase(),     Changes the casing of the string.,            str.toLowerCase();
equals(Object obj),                Compares the content of two strings.,         str1.equals(str2);
contains(CharSequence s),          Checks if a sequence is present.,             str.contains(""Java"");




// BAD WAY: Using String in a loop
String s = "";
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    s = s + i; // Creates 5 different string objects
}

// GOOD WAY: Using StringBuilder
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    sb.append(i); // Modifies the SAME object
}

String finalResult = sb.toString(); // Convert back to String when done
System.out.println(finalResult); // "01234"
